===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|countable|sometimes|in the plural}} The remains of a destroyed or dilapidated construction, such as a house or castle.
#* {{w|Joseph Addison}} (1672–1719)
#*: The Veian and the Gabian towers shall fall, / And one promiscuous '''ruin''' cover all; / Nor, after length of years, a stone betray / The place where once the very '''ruins''' lay.
#* {{w|Joseph Stevens Buckminster}} (1751-1812)
#*: The labour of a day will not build up a virtuous habit on the '''ruins''' of an old and vicious character.
#* {{quote-book|year=1963|author={{w|Margery Allingham}}|title={{w|The China Governess}}
|chapter=Foreword|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL2004261W
|passage=A canister of flour from the kitchen had been thrown at the looking-glass and lay like trampled snow over the remains of a decent blue suit with the lining ripped out which lay on top of the '''ruin''' of a plastic wardrobe.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The state of being a ruin, destroyed or decayed.
#: {{ux|en|The monastery has fallen into '''ruin'''.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} Something that leads to serious trouble or destruction.
#: {{ux|en|Gambling has been the '''ruin''' of many.}}
#* {{w|Francis Bacon}} (1561-1626)
#*: The errors of young men are the '''ruin''' of business.
#* {{RQ:RnhrtHpwd Bat|I|01}}
#*: The Bat—they called him the Bat.{{nb...}}. He{{...}}played a lone hand,{{nb...}}. Most lone wolves had a moll at any rate—women were their '''ruin'''—but if the Bat had a moll, not even the grapevine telegraph could locate her.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[fall]] or [[tumble]].
#* {{w|George Chapman}} (1559-1634)
#*: His '''ruin''' startled the other steeds.
# A change that destroys or defeats something; destruction; overthrow.
#: {{ux|en|the '''ruin''' of a ship or an army;&emsp; {{nowrap|the '''ruin''' of a constitution or a government;}}&emsp; {{nowrap|the '''ruin''' of health or hopes}}}}
#* {{w|Thomas Gray}} (1716-1771)
#*: '''Ruin''' seize thee, ruthless king!

